<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900726-0029</DOCNO><DOCID>900726-0029.</DOCID><HL>   Panel Clears Bill to Donate   Properties to Aid Homeless</HL><DATE>07/26/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><IN>REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)</IN><GV>CONGRESS (CNG)HOUSING AND URBAN DEVELOPMENT (HUD)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Senate Governmental Affairs Committeeapproved legislation allowing the donation of surplus federalproperty to non-profit groups working with homeless people.   Currently, the government grants limited-term leases tosuch qualified groups, an arrangement that public-interestorganizations have argued prohibits them from makinglong-range plans.</LP><TEXT>   Assistant Housing Secretary Anna Kondratas said theadministration welcomed the measure and would use itsregulatory authority to start deeding properties even beforefinal passage of the measure, which the committee approved byvoice vote.   Deeding the property to groups dealing with the homelesswill make &quot;a significant difference&quot; in the program becausethe lease arrangement currently thwarts those groups fromsecuring the financing needed to improve the facilities, saidWendy Adler, of the National Governors' Association.   The McKinney Homeless Assistance Act of 1987 is theprimary federal vehicle for aiding the homeless. But criticshave charged that one of its major programs, thesurplus-property program, has been less effective than itcould be because of government inefficiency and insufficientinformation on available properties.   &quot;There is still no comprehensive federal guidance on howto obtain federal vacant properties,&quot; John Ols, the directorof housing and community development issues of the GeneralAccounting Office, said last week in testmony before thecommittee.</TEXT></DOC>